<div id="review_1420042978" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1420042978" />
    <a title="Andreea" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1417076-andreea"><img alt="Andreea" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1395578865p2/1417076.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1420042978?book_show_action=true">Oct 19, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andreea" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andreea" href="/user/show/1417076-andreea">Andreea</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1420042978" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10617423152734059104">Can I give no star to this book? No? Okay. Let&apos;s start. I AM SO GLAD I FINALLY FINISHED IT because it was going on and on forever with no purpose. Why I hate it, you ask? Because it pretends to be something it&apos;s not and has an annoying main character. It&apos;s the best example for how not to write a book. You know the &quot;show, don&apos;t tell&quot; advice that writers give a lot? THIS BOOK IS ONLY SAYING AND TELLING AND HOPES THE WORDS BECOME SHOW. But you can&apos;t say the character changed and evolved (and it&apos;s n</span>
  <span id="freeText10617423152734059104" style="display:none">Can I give no star to this book? No? Okay. Let's start. I AM SO GLAD I FINALLY FINISHED IT because it was going on and on forever with no purpose. Why I hate it, you ask? Because it pretends to be something it's not and has an annoying main character. It's the best example for how not to write a book. You know the "show, don't tell" advice that writers give a lot? THIS BOOK IS ONLY SAYING AND TELLING AND HOPES THE WORDS BECOME SHOW. But you can't say the character changed and evolved (and it's not superficial anymore or blah blah) but he continues to act the way it always did. <br /><br />I do not hate unlikable main characters or anything, but only when they are portrayed that way intentionally. But I have a feeling the author (the book is a bit semi-autobiographical or something) actually believes this character is right and not the superficial d*ck he is!!!<br /><br />And another thing that annoys me is HOW EVERYONE AND THEIR MOTHER (and my mother, cause I read this book because she likes Coelho) pretend this author is some brilliant spiritual guy or something. Don't get me wrong, I have no problem with bad books being popular or bad writers being popular - hell, I really enjoy Dan Brown's novels - but usually those books know what they are and accept it and have no problem. But this guy and his books pretend to be the gem of the literature and the best creation ever. <br /><br />Ih! So glad I finished the book and I am pretty sure I will not make myself read another one of his books. Also, I know mum likes his books but I won't buy them any for her birthday because I do not want to support this guy - and she'll be happier if I get her cute oven mittens or a new hoover!</span>
  <a data-text-id="10617423152734059104" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


